Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** to create an in-memory test server, then pass its `HttpClient` into the MCP SDK's transport. This gives you full protocol coverage with no real network listener.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol  # MCP C# SDK
```

### Example test (xUnit)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient wired
        // to the in-memory test server — no port, no network.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use the SDK's Streamable HTTP transport, injecting
        // the test HttpClient so it never hits the network.
        var options = new SseClientTransportOptions
        {
            Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
            Name = "test-client"
        };

        var transport = new SseClientTransport(options, httpClient);
        await using var client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var tools = await client.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsResult()
    {
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        var options = new SseClientTransportOptions
        {
            Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
            Name = "test-client"
        };

        var transport = new SseClientTransport(options, httpClient);
        await using var client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await client.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains(result.Content,
            c => c.Text?.Contains("expected output") == true);
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts your app in-process with an in-memory test server |
| **Real HTTP pipeline** | Middleware, routing, DI — everything runs exactly as in production |
| **Transport** | Pass the factory's `HttpClient` into `SseClientTransport` (or `StreamableHttpClientTransport` if your server uses the newer streamable HTTP) so the MCP SDK talks to the in-memory server |
| **`Program` class** | Ensure your server project exposes a `Program` class (add `public partial class Program { }` at the bottom of `Program.cs` if using top-level statements) |
| **Customization** | Override `WebApplicationFactory.ConfigureWebHost` to swap services (e.g., mock databases) for test isolation |

This approach exercises the full MCP JSON-RPC protocol, serialization, and your tool/resource handlers end-to-end.
